    <div class="nhsuk-grid-column-two-thirds">


        <h2 id="when-to-use-this-component">When to use this component</h2>
            <p>Use the fieldset component when you need to show a relationship between multiple form inputs. For example, you may need to group a set of text inputs into a single fieldset when asking for an address.</p>
										
            <h2 >Code and design</h2>

            <h3>Fieldset</h3>

            <div class="example grey-background nhsuk-u-margin-bottom-4">


                
                    {% from 'components/fieldset/macro.njk' import fieldset %}

                    {{ fieldset({
                    "legend": {
                        "text": "What is your address?"
                    }
                    }) }}


            </div>

        


            <p><a href="https://nhsuk.github.io/nhsuk-frontend/components/fieldset/index.html">Preview the fieldset component</a></p>
            <p>You can <a href="https://github.com/nhsuk/nhsuk-frontend/tree/master/packages/components/fieldset">get the latest fieldset component code</a> in the NHS.UK frontend library in GitHub.</p>
            

            <h3>Fieldset as page heading</h3>

                <div class="example grey-background nhsuk-u-margin-bottom-4">
                    {% from 'components/fieldset/macro.njk' import fieldset %}

                        {{ fieldset({
                        "legend": {
                            "text": "What is your address?",
                            "classes": "nhsuk-fieldset__legend--xl",
                            "isPageHeading": true
                        }
                        }) }}
                </div>

            <p><a href="https://nhsuk.github.io/nhsuk-frontend/components/fieldset/page-heading.html">Preview the Fieldset as page heading component</a></p>
            <p>You can <a href="https://github.com/nhsuk/nhsuk-frontend/tree/master/packages/components/fieldset">get the latest Fieldset as page heading component code</a> in the NHS.UK frontend library in GitHub.</p>


            <h2 id="how-it-works">How fieldset works</h2>
                <p class="rich-text">The first element inside a fieldset must be a <code>legend</code> which describes the group of inputs. This could be a question, such as ‘What is your current address?’ or a statement like ‘Personal details’.</p>
                <p class="rich-text">If you’re asking just <a href="https://design-system.service.gov.uk/patterns/question-pages/#start-by-asking-one-question-per-page">one question per page</a> as recommended by GOV.UK Design System, you can set the contents of the <code>&lt;legend&gt;</code> as the page heading, as shown in the example below. This is good practice as it means that users of screen readers will only hear the contents once.</p>

                <p>Read more about <a href="https://design-system.service.gov.uk/get-started/labels-legends-headings/">why and how GOV.UK Design System set legends as headings</a>.</p>

            <h3>Accessibility</h3>
                <p>On question pages containing a group of inputs, including the question as the legend helps users of screenreaders to understand that the inputs are all related to that question.</p>
                <p>Include any general help text which is important for filling in the form and cannot be written as <a href="/patterns/hint-text">hint text</a> in the legend, but try to keep it as concise as possible.</p>

            <h2>Research</h2>
